{{Quote|They were worried my story might get out. So, they erased me. My history. But they've been doing that for five hundred years. Pledge allegiance to that, my brother. They will never let a Black man be Captain America. And even if they did, no self-respecting Black man would ever wanna be.|Isaiah Bradley to [[Sam Wilson]]|Truth}}
'''Isaiah Bradley''' is a {{WPS|Korean War}} veteran who was unwillingly subjected to human testings of the [[Super Soldier Serum]] in the [[1950s]]. A survivor of the trials, he was assigned by the [[United States Armed Forces|United States military]] to eliminate [[Winter Soldier]] in [[South Korea]], although he failed. When the government feared the ramifications of an African-American super soldier, Bradley spent three decades incarcerated in prison, during which he was experimented on by the U.S. government and [[Hydra]]. In the [[1980s]], he was freed and was relocated to [[Baltimore]] after his death was faked, during which he raised a [[Eli Bradley|grandson]]. In [[2024]], when [[Sam Wilson]] became the new Captain America, Bradley's heroics were memorialized at the [[Smithsonian Institution|Smithsonian National Air and Space Museum]].

Becoming Wilson's personal trainer, Bradley received an invitation to the [[White House]] to attend an [[Celestial Island World Summit|event]] held by President [[Thaddeus Ross]] regarding the signing of a [[Ozaki-Ross Accords|new treaty]]. However, in the middle of Ross' speech, Bradley entered a trance-like state and suddenly [[Attack on President Ross|shot]] at the President before fleeing into [[Washington, D.C.]] Unaware of what had occurred, Bradley was taken into [[Joint Base Anacostia–Bolling|custody]] while awaiting trial, where they would determine whether or not he would receive the death penalty. Wilson eventually proved Bradley's innocence by exposing [[Samuel Sterns]] as the mastermind behind the attack via mind control techniques he had developed in secrecy, and Bradley was released from prison.

==Biography==
{{MD|Isaiah Bradley (Earth-199999)}}
===Korean War===
====Becoming a Super Soldier====
{{Quote|A handful of us got shot up with different versions of that [[Super Soldier Serum|serum]], but they don't tell us what it is.|Isaiah Bradley to [[Sam Wilson]]|Truth}}
Following [[Steve Rogers]]' apparent death during [[World War II]], the [[United States of America]] attempted to recreate the [[Super Soldier Serum]] in order to create more super soldiers. During the [[Cold War]], the [[United States Armed Forces]] produced several different versions and used African-American soldiers as test subjects, lying to the men that they were being given tetanus shots. However, out of all of the different serum versions they had created, only one was sufficiently recreated, which had been solely administered to soldier Isaiah Bradley.{{Ref|TFaTWS105}}

====Encountering Winter Soldier====
{{Quote|We heard whispers [[Winter Soldier|he]] was on the [[Korea|peninsula]], but everyone they sent after him, never came back. So the [[United States of America|U.S.]] [[United States Armed Forces|military]] dropped me behind the line to go deal with him.|Isaiah Bradley to [[Sam Wilson]]|The Star-Spangled Man}}
With the [[United States]] now in possession of a troop of super soldiers, the men were sent on combat missions. In [[1951]], during the {{WPS|Korean War}}, the U.S. military found out that an [[Winter Soldier|enemy soldier]] managed to kill everyone they sent after him. As a result, the military deployed Bradley, their super soldier, to eliminate the threat. Bradley found his target at a bar in [[Goyang]], who was none other than the Winter Soldier. While Bradley was unable to kill Winter Soldier, he was able to discover his identity and destroyed half of his metal arm, after which Winter Soldier fled. This incident, among others, gained Bradley a reputation as one of [[Hydra]]'s most feared enemies.{{Ref|TFaTWS102}}

====Liberation of the Super Soldiers====
{{Quote|A couple of the boys get captured on a mission. I heard the brass talkin' about blowing the POW camp to hell to hide the evidence. But those were my men. My brothers. Not evidence. So I bust out of the facility one night and I brought them boys back.|Isaiah Bradley to [[Sam Wilson]]|Truth}}
Bradley's fellow soldiers, who had received the imperfect variants of the [[Super Soldier Serum]], found themselves becoming unstable and dying. No longer able to perform their combat duties adequately, they were quickly captured by enemy forces and placed in a POW camp. Realizing that their unethical experiments on African-American men could come to light, the [[United States Armed Forces]] decided to destroy the POW camp with an air strike to eliminate the super soldiers and hide the evidence. Wishing to save his friends, Bradley single-handedly infiltrated and liberated the camp, freeing his fellow super soldiers and returning them to their base. However, the soldiers whom he had saved quickly died, having succumbed to the side effects of the imperfect serum given to them.{{Ref|TFaTWS105}}

===Imprisonment===
====Experimented====
{{Quote|For the next thirty years, they experimented on me, trying to figure out why the [[Super Soldier Serum|serum]] worked.|Isaiah Bradley to [[Sam Wilson]]|Truth}}
Despite his service to the [[United States of America]] in the {{WPS|Korean War}}, Bradley was punished for disobeying orders and saving his fellow super soldiers. As a result, Bradley was put in prison for thirty years. During that time, scientists, including members of the [[CIA]] and [[Hydra]],{{Ref|TFaTWS102}} experimented and took his blood, trying to replicate the version of the [[Super Soldier Serum]] he had been given.

While incarcerated, he wrote letters to his wife [[Faith Bradley]], although his captors did not send them to her. Faith, who had been pregnant with Bradley's child, had sent him letters as well, believing he was still fighting in [[Korea]]. In one of these letters, she included a photo of their newborn son, although Bradley was not made privy to this information as the military did not pass on her letters to him. Instead, they decided to inform Faith that Bradley had been killed in action. Sometime during Bradley's thirty-year incarceration, Faith passed away.{{Ref|TFaTWS105}}

====Freedom====
{{Quote|There was a nurse. She took pity on me. Wrote up some fake reports, something. She had me declared dead.|Isaiah Bradley to [[Sam Wilson]]|Truth}}
In the [[1980s]], one of the nurses took pity on his fate and chose to ease his suffering. As the military had kept all the letters Bradley had tried sending to his wife [[Faith Bradley|Faith]] along with the letters his wife had sent him, the nurse acquired them and passed them on to Bradley. Additionally, she faked his death and helped him escape the facility.{{Ref|TFaTWS105}} Upon being freed, he relocated to [[Baltimore]], [[Maryland]] where his teenager grandson, [[Eli Bradley]], lived. Living with Eli, who helped take care of him and he to him, Bradley informed Eli of his history and instructed him not to tell anyone of his existence.{{Ref|TFaTWS102}}

===Life in Baltimore===
====Reunion with Bucky Barnes====
[[File:Isaiah Bradley.png|{{AltFloat}}|Bradley meets [[Bucky Barnes]] and [[Sam Wilson]]]]
{{Quote|You think you can wake up one day and decide who you wanna be? It doesn't work like that. Well, maybe it does for folks like you.|Isaiah Bradley to [[Bucky Barnes]]|The Star-Spangled Man}}
The location of Bradley's [[Bradley Residence|residence]] was eventually discovered by [[Bucky Barnes]], although Barnes chose not to tell anyone about it, choosing to respect Bradley's desire to stay hidden. In [[2024]], Bradley was visited at his house by Barnes and [[Sam Wilson]], who asked for his assistance as they wished to find out how the [[Super Soldier Serum]] had been recreated once more.
[[File:Isaiah Bradley (2024).png|{{AltFloat}}|Bradley furiously demands to be left alone]]
However, Bradley refused to help them, having only agreed to allow them entry to see whether Barnes was still alive, noting that he had gained a new [[Winter Soldier's Prosthetic Arm|metal arm]] since he had torn the last one off and in morbid curiosity in case Barnes had come to kill him. When Barnes asked for more information about how the serum could've been recreated, Bradley reacted in anger, using his enhanced strength to fling a metal can into the wall, embedding itself. He then demanded that Barnes and Wilson leave his house and Eli ushered the two outside.{{Ref|TFaTWS102}}

====Speaking with Sam Wilson====
[[File:Isaiah Bradley talks to Sam Wilson.png|{{AltFloat}}|Bradley being reunited with [[Sam Wilson]]]]
{{Quote|You think things are different? You think times are different? You think I wouldn't be dead in a day if you brought me out? You wanna believe jail was my fault because you got that [[Steve Rogers|white man]]'s [[Captain America's Shield|shield]].|Isaiah Bradley to [[Sam Wilson]]|Truth}}
A few days later, Bradley was out watering his plants in his backyard, when [[Sam Wilson]] returned to see him. Bradley let Wilson into his backyard and then told Wilson not to get [[Captain America's Shield]] out of its case, after Wilson had asked if he wanted to see it.
[[File:Isaiah Bradley & Sam Wilson.png|{{AltFloat}}|Bradley telling [[Sam Wilson]] about his history]]
Having let Wilson inside, Bradley and Wilson sat in the living room, and Bradley answered Wilson's questions. He also recalled his past having taken the [[Super Soldier Serum]] and what his life was like because of it, getting emotional at times. Bradley told Wilson that due to his Super Soldier abilities he was able to combat against the Winter Soldier when they crossed paths. When the subject of being Captain America came up, he told Wilson that no black man would ever hold that mantle and was convinced of that sentiment due to his past experiences.{{Ref|TFaTWS105}}

====Isaiah Bradley Exhibit====
[[File:Eli and Isaiah watch Falcon.png|{{AltFloat}}|Bradley watches the [[WHiH World News|news]]]]
{{Quote|You ain't no {{WPS|Malcolm X|Malcolm}}, {{WPS|Martin Luther King, Jr.|Martin}}, {{WPS|Nelson Mandela|Mandela}}, but..."<br>"No argument there. But I know what I've gotta do."<br>"So, a Black Captain America, huh?|Isaiah Bradley and [[Sam Wilson]]|One World, One People}}
In the summer, as Bradley and Eli were eating dinner, they stopped eating to watch the [[WHiH World News|news]] live feed of [[Captain America]] giving his speech to the [[GRC]] officials and the public.
[[File:Isaiah Bradley & Captain America.png|{{AltFloat}}|Bradley speaks with [[Sam Wilson]]]]
The next day, Bradley was out in his yard tending to his plants when [[Sam Wilson]] arrived. Bradley then walked over to talk with him, telling Wilson that he heard the GRC had halted voting on the [[Patch Act]] due to Wilson's speech. He then told Wilson that he was no {{WPS|Malcolm X}}, {{WPS|Martin Luther King Jr.}} or {{WPS|Nelson Mandela}} and that Wilson taking on the Captain America mantle would not be easy. Bradley was then asked by Wilson to go with him to see something.
[[File:Isaiah Bradley exhibit.png|{{AltFloat}}|Bradley sees his exhibit]]
Wilson then took Bradley and Eli to [[Washington, D.C.]] and to the [[Smithsonian Institution|Smithsonian National Air and Space Museum]]. There they walked through the updated Captain America exhibit and in the next room, Bradley saw a statue dedicated to him and a memorial plaque detailing his history of service to the United States. Upon seeing the exhibit, Bradley became emotional and hugged Wilson.{{Ref|TFaTWS106}}

